  1. The Owner shall record the Development Agreement in the real property records of Grand County simultaneously with the approving Ordinance and prior to application for further site plan, construction, or development approvals.
     **Background:** The subject property is zoned Range and Grazing and is currently undeveloped and surrounded by BLM land, which is predominantly used for recreation and natural wildlife habitat, and resource extraction.
  
  This is a request for the OAO-Campground/RV District to be applied to a portion of Parcel 24-0XST-0067 for the purpose of developing a luxury eco-retreat centered on environmentally responsible tourism. The OAO proposal includes a request to rezone 544 acres of the roughly 1,130 acre parcel. The property owner (Intrepid- Potash Moab, LLC) intends to later subdivide the 1,130-acre parcel, partitioning off 544 acres, which is the subject of this rezone, and as such the full property area is not included in this request.
  
  The OAO development includes plans for 16 luxury tent sites, activity center, restaurant, bar and swimming pools, as well as five on-site employee housing units as permitted per LUC section 3.3.2.D, Accessory Employee Housing. The developer estimates that the resort will generate up to 50 jobs with a much higher pay rate than the present-day average wage in Grand County.
  
  This application is a resubmission. In 2022 the developer brought forth this proposal but was denied at that time: Commission stating concerns with the relatively high ratio of overnight accommodations to primary dwellings in the County, and the development agreement lacking sufficient provision to ensure deed restricted employee housing that would offset the development’s impact. The Commission also cited concerns with the development’s impact on the viewshed and the surrounding area, being located within the boundary of the Scenic Resource Protection District. At the time, the developer had plans for implementing a conservation easement for a large portion of the property, but the Development Agreement did not include any mechanism for ensuring the conservation easement would be executed and the open space would be preserved in perpetuity.
  
  The developer has resubmitted the application with a revised Development Agreement which includes provisions for on site and off site employee housing, as well as deed restricted open space to be preserved in perpetuity.
  
  The employee housing proposal brought forth by the developer includes a commitment to construct 15 off-site employee housing units located within Grand County, to be deed restricted for Actively Employed Households, per LUC Section 4.7. This proposal is in addition to a commitment to construct 5 on-site employee housing units, as permitted per LUC section 3.3 - Accessory Uses and Structures. Both the on-site and off-site employee housing is required to be constructed within 24 months of Site Plan approval, and prior to Certificate of Occupancy is issued for the resort.
  
  Additionally, the applicant has entered into a Deed Restriction Agreement with the neighboring property (Red
  Earth Venue, a special event venue) for the purpose of Open Space preservation of 104 acres of land
  surrounding the Venue, including a portion of the 313 Scenic Byway. Because the property owner’s intent is to
  later subdivide that portion of property which is the subject of the OAO rezone request, the Deed Restricted
  area does not include the remainder of the property (outside of the development area to the east).
  
  The Development Agreement requires that such Proposal for Dedication of Open Space in Perpetuity be
  finalized and recorded prior to obtaining final Site Plan approval.
  
  The developer intends to further protect the natural landscapes within the Deed Restricted area, through a
  conservation easement. The applicant has included a letter provided by Utah Open Lands Conservation
  Association which explains that while the Association cannot provide a guarantee of conservation easement
  until the property owner of record (Mr. Kareus has interest in the property but is not yet the owner) requests the
  initiation of review, the Association does in fact “recognize this location as a priority conservation region” as it
  is nearby other Utah Open Lands areas, including: Brown Moab Ranch, Mulberry Grove Open Space,
  Arrowhead Preserve, Castleton Tower Preserve, Parriott Mesa Preserve, Professor Valley Ranch, and the
  various Mountain Island Ranch conserved lands.
  
  The Development Agreement includes language legally binding the developer to such terms of development
  and defines terms of default from the agreement which could result in the revocation, denial, or suspension of
  any permit, including a land development permit, conditional use permit, building permit, certificate of
  occupancy, or discretionary approval.
  
  Overall, the applicant has demonstrated that the project largely complies with the OAO standards, designing an
  energy efficient, luxury eco-retreat with no more than 16 tent sites proposed. Development of camping
  accommodations will be built within a modest footprint, relative to the 544-acre property. The applicant will
  need to provide evidence of a water right sufficient to support the development as well as preliminary
  engineering studies showing the feasibility of providing a water source and ability to dispose of waste water on
  site.
  
  At Site Plan review, the project will be reviewed against the development standards of Section 4.8.4 Scenic
  Resource Protection District and all other applicable section of the LUC.
  
