  ## Exhibit A
  
  ## Narrative Summary
  
  ## Narrative summarizing the proposed development of the property by gross acre;
  
  ## number of lots or units, common area and open space acreage, overall character
  
  ## and architectural style, and other related development features as proposed by
  
  ## the developer or requested by the County;
  
  Entrada Moab will be a world-class luxury tented camp inspired by both the iconic safari camps of southern Africa and the mesmerizing beauty of the Utah desert. Utilizing concepts of biophilic design, the camp will blend in seamlessly with its surroundings, blurring the boundary between the manmade and natural worlds. Designed with the lightest possible footprint, the camp will use minimal hard infrastructure so that it may eventually be packed up and removed without a trace. Entrada Camps and Conservation’s (ECC) stringent sustainability code emphasizes the use of renewable energy produced onsite and sustainable building materials and practices; adhering to the strictest standards of energy, water, carbon and waste reduction; sourcing food and other goods and services locally whenever possible; and preserving biodiversity and protecting open space.
  
  Please see Appendix C to view our conceptual site plan, project renderings and design information.
  
  With 16 guest tents (12 double occupancy and four family units) on 544-acres, the camp will be situated discreetly in a huge box canyon so as to be almost invisible from UT-313. All structures will encompass less than one-percent of the acreage and our focus will be on preservation of the property’s natural landscape, flora, and fauna as well as the viewshed from UT-313. To this end, ECC plans to place a portion of the property along UT-313 (approximately100 acres) under permanent deed restriction, protecting it from future development and preserving the scenic viewshed along this section of Highway 313. We have committed to the deed restriction as part of our proposed Development Agreement with Grand County and we have entered into a separate, formal agreement (see Appendix A) with a neighboring property owner committing ourselves to follow through with the deed restriction if our application is approved. Furthermore, it is our intention to pursue a permanent conservation easement on this section of the property in the future. We have initiated discussions with Utah Open Lands about the conservation easement and have attached a letter of support from them (see Appendix B) for our project.
  
  * * *
  
  Please note: the land we are under contract to purchase from Intrepid Potash constitutes roughly half of the total parcel they own at this location. If this application is successful and we purchase the property, we will legally subdivide it and the OAO will only apply to the 544 acres we will have purchased. The property map included with this application illustrates the section we are under contract to purchase and the area of the proposed easement.
  
  In addition to the guest tents, facilities will include a main lodge tent featuring a full-service restaurant and bar and indoor and outdoor lounge areas. Other facilities include an activity center, a storage building and two small swimming pools.
  
  Our vision is for Entrada Moab to be a fully inclusive experience, which will encourage guests to remain on the property as much as possible. This will help minimize the impact we will have on other natural areas, including national parks, and on the town of Moab. The property will also offer many onsite activities, such as rock climbing, hiking and mountain biking. World-class naturalist guides will educate our guests about the unique ecology, geology and natural history of the area and inspire them to become informed and engaged participants in its ongoing protection.
  
  With just 16 guest tents, Entrada Moab will have a nominal impact on Grand County’s overall visitor capacity, but with nightly projected rates of $2,000, will make a significant contribution to the county tax base and economy. We project that our annual Transient Room Tax payments will be approximately equal to those of a 150-room hotel charging $200 per night.
  
  In addition, we are sensitive to the fact that tourism growth in the county has created a shortage of affordable employee housing there. As such, in our Development Agreement we have committed to providing five onsite and 15 off site employee housing units in order to offset any negative impact on the ratio of employee housing units to overnight rentals and to ensure our employees have adequate, affordable housing.
  
  ECC has signed a letter of intent to partner with Luxury Frontiers (see Appendix D) on the design and development of Entrada Moab. Luxury Frontiers is the world’s premiere developer of sustainable luxury resorts and is renowned for sustainable and immersive design in some of the most naturally beautiful locations across the globe. Their work includes Camp Sarika at Amangiri in southern Utah and, more recently, Camp Naviva at the Four Seasons in Punta Mita, Mexico. Luxury Frontiers properties are routinely listed as some of the best hotels in the world by Conde Nast Travel, Travel and Leisure and other top travel publications (see Appendix E). In 2020, Camp Sarika was the Grand Prize recipient of the prestigious Radical Innovation Award, which honors compelling innovations in travel, sustainability, hospitality, and architecture.
  
  ## About Entrada Camps and Conservation (ECC)
  
  ECC is dedicated to setting new standards for sustainability, service and luxury for the hospitality industry in the American West. Inspired by the iconic luxury safari camps of Africa, our tented resorts are located in some of the world's most dramatically beautiful natural settings and provide guests with deeply immersive and transformational experiences.
  
  Our model of low-impact, high value tourism is designed to provide real economic benefits to local communities and people, minimize the negative effects of tourism growth on already over-touristed places, preserve biodiversity and protect open space, and to be a force for the conservation of the natural world.
  
  ## Our Values
  
  **Sustainability** Our tented camps will be designed and built to have the least possible impact on the land and surrounding environments. With a maximum of just 16 guest suites, we strive to minimize the use of hard infrastructure so that all facilities may eventually be removed without a trace. We employ cutting edge technologies to generate sustainable energy, minimize our energy and water needs, and reduce waste.
  
  ## Conservation & Stewardship
  
  Wildlife and habitat conservation are at the heart of everything we do. A crucial tenet of our mission is to acquire and protect large tracts of land in sensitive natural areas and to preserve critical wildlife habitat. And through our non-profit Entrada Foundation, we will donate 1% of our gross revenue (not profits) to support community conservation initiatives and will actively educate our guests about local conservation issues and provide them with a mechanism to donate themselves.
  
  ## Community & People
  
  We are deeply committed to being good, engaged citizens of the communities where we operate. As such, we strive to contribute meaningfully to local economies, support local people and enhance their quality of life. Our model of low-impact, high value tourism (a small number of rooms sold at a very high rate) ensures that we will have minimal impact on the overall visitor capacity of our destinations, while allowing us to contribute significantly to the local tax base and to pay above market salaries and benefits to our staff. We strive to provide our staff with highly competitive salaries and benefits packages, world-class hospitality training, and ample opportunities for career growth and advancement.
  
  ## Our Team
  
  ## Matt Kareus
  
  A fifth generation descendent of western Colorado homesteaders, Matt was born and raised near Fruita, where he developed a deep and abiding love for the wild places and landscapes of the American southwest. He is a 25-year veteran of the adventure travel industry and has served in senior leadership positions for some of the top tour operators in the world. For 13 years, he served as marketing director for Natural Habitat Adventures and helped establish the company as one of the world’s largest and most respected nature and wildlife travel companies and spearheaded its groundbreaking conservation partnerships and sustainability initiatives. He is motivated by the belief that travel, at its best, can be a powerful force for good in the world, one that connects people and benefits communities and acts as a tool for the preservation and conservation of the natural world. Since 2011, he has served as the Executive Director of the International Galapagos Tour Operators Association, which promotes sustainable and responsible travel to Darwin’s famed archipelago and has raised over $1 million to support wildlife conservation there. He also serves on the board of the Natural Selection Foundation, which uses the power of tourism to promote wildlife conservation and help protect vast expanses of African wilderness.
  
  ## Luxury Frontiers
  
  Entrada Camps and Conservation is partnering with Luxury Frontiers on the design and development of Entrada Moab. Luxury Frontiers designs sustainable and immersive resorts and lodges in naturally beautiful locations all over the globe. Specializing in architecture, interior design, procurement, project management, and strategic advisory services, the firm offers an end-to-end scope of services to position an asset for success in today’s ever-evolving hospitality landscape.
  
  Innovating the design space for the experiential lodging sector, Luxury Frontiers is known for creating upmarket tented camps, treetop suites, and other rare and iconic hospitality structures. Driven to bring people closer to nature, without sacrificing sustainability or sophistication, Luxury Frontiers helps clients create meaningful journeys for their guests through strategic planning and award-winning design.
  
  In 2020, Luxury Frontiers won the international Radical Innovation Award for designing and building Camp Sarika, the tented camp at the luxury Amangiri Resort near Canyon Point, Utah. The award honors compelling ideas that push the hospitality industry forward through creative vision, design, feasibility, and impact. In addition to numerous other awards for design and sustainability, Luxury Frontiers’ creations are routinely listed among the best hotels in the world by Travel & Leisure, Condé Nast Traveler and other publications. Awards and press coverage in 2022 include:
  
  - TRAVEL + LEISURE, The 100 Best Hotels in the World: Nayara Tented Camp
  - TRAVEL + LEISURE, The 10 Best Resorts in Central America: Nayara Tented Camp
