  ## B. Water
  
  See section 4.6.7.C.2.f below.
  
  ## C. Transportation
  
  ECC Moab is expected to have a similar trip generation rate as a vacation rental or motel unit. Per the Institute of Traffic Engineers (ITE), we expect to generate 6.1 trips per day for a total of 97 trips per day. This is a very minimal amount of traffic and should not decrease the level of service on State Road 313. The resort will also have vehicles and staff who will take guests out for activities. This will help to minimize the traffic generated by the resort by twenty percent (20%) as required by Section 4.6.5.C.2
  
  The parking lot for employees and guests will have two electric vehicle charging stations as required per Section 4.6.5.C.1.d.
  
  The proposed parking lot has space to accommodate a shuttle stop.
  
  ## D. Mixed Use
  
  The development is providing onsite housing for five (5) employees, which is the maximum number of units allowed per the county’s land use code. Section 6.15.4.A – Assured Housing Requirements calls for developers to deed restrict affordable housing for hotel/motel, condo, townhome and high end single family residential projects. Because this project was classified as an RV/Campground for the purpose of the OAO application, the assured housing requirement does not apply.
  
  ## E. Open Space
  
  The resort facilities will occupy less than 1% of the 544-acre property. This large amount of open space exceeds the 25% requirement per Section 4.6.5.E.1.d-Design Standards in the OAO District.
  
  * * *
  
  The property is currently zoned Range and Grazing, which, according to the county land use code, allows for the development of one residential homesite per acre and a variety of commercial uses. Entrada Moab will prevent the vast majority of the property from being developed and will focus on maintaining it in its current state. To this end, ECC has agreed to place approximately 100 acres of the property along UT-313 under permanent deed restriction in its proposed Developed Agreement and has entered into a separate, formal agreement with a neighboring property owner to do the same. The deed restriction will prevent development on that section of the property and protect the viewshed along this section of UT-313 in perpetuity. ECC intends to eventually place this section of the property in a permanent conservation easement and has included a letter of support for this application from Utah Open Lands.
  
  ## F. Height
  
  There will be no structures near ridgelines.
  
  The adventure center and the guest units are approximately 3⁄4 of a mile away from Highway 313. All structures are designed to be hidden from view from the highway.
  
  The height of the guest units is relatively low as shown on the renderings in Appendix C.
  
  The location of the resort in the box canyon will not affect the views of neighboring property owners.
  
  ## G. Density and Scale
  
  This project does not contain any hotels, motels or residential development. The requirements of Section 4.6.5.G.1 and 2 do not apply. Section 4.6.5.G.3 states the maximum number of spaces in an RV/campground is 60 spaces. Only 16 guest units are proposed for this project.
  
  ## H. Site Configuration
  
  The center of the resort will be located approximately 3⁄4 of a mile away from Highway
  
  313. Structures will be designed and placed to be nearly unnoticeable from Highway
  314. Proposed guest units and other structures are relatively small in size and will be placed near the base of the mountain in relatively flat areas. No mass grading is needed for this project.
