  To Whom It May Concern,
  
  Matt Kareus reached out to Utah Open Lands recently to initiate the process of placing a conservation easement on a portion of a property of interest to him in order to protect open space and the view shed along Deadhorse Mesa Scenic Byway (313) which leads to Dead Horse State Park and Canyonlands National Park. Utah Open Lands can only move forward with projects that an interested party owns as we are a non-profit with limited resources. This project has not moved forward as Mr. Kareus is not the current owner. Were he to become the landowner, Utah Open Lands would certainly consider this Property initially to begin to work through the conservation process. For any property, Utah Open Lands cannot issue a guarantee that we will hold any conservation easement without a project going through our full approval process, which includes multiple reviews by our Conservation Subcommittee and Board of Directors.
  
  Utah Open Lands is always willing to consider the potential of lands for open space protection and public benefit. Utah Open Lands holds many conservation easements in the Moab area, and this is a priority conservation region for our organization. Based on an initial review of this property, it does retain potential conservation values which would qualify it as a potential conservation easement project for the organization, however retained permitted uses and ground truthing of the remote data we have reviewed thus far would affect Utah Open Lands ultimate decision regarding how this property fits within our conservation criteria. Based on a review of unground-truthed data, the Property potentially represents habitat for Bobcat, Chukar, Mountain Lion, and Desert Bighorn Sheep. The Property also likely represents key habitats as defined by Utah DWR such as Desert Grassland, Gambel Oak, Lowland Sagebrush, Mountain Sagebrush, Mountain Shrub, and Riparian. The property is adjacent to vast BLM tracts of land. The property is nearby other Utah Open Lands Conserved Lands to include: Brown Moab Ranch, Mulberry Grove Open Space, Lasal Herd Critical Range Preserve, Arrowhead Preserve, Castleton Tower Preserve, Fryer Family Scenic Preserve, Parriott Mesa Preserve, Professor Valley Ranch, Professor Valley Mary Jane Canyon, Fisher Valley Century Ranch and the various Mountain Island Ranch conserved lands. Being situated along the entry route for Dead Horse State Park and Canyonlands National Park, along with adjacency to Deadhorse Mesa Scenic Byway, and representing beautiful canyonlands, this Property also potentially provides a scenic respite for substantial numbers of Utah and U.S. citizens (along with international tourists attracted to the sites).
  
  Please feel free to contact Utah Opens Lands with any questions at (801) 463-6156.
  
