  Re: ECC Statement on Employee Housing
  
  Dear Grand County Commission,
  
  We understand the impact that tourism growth has had on housing in Grand County. In recent years, demand for labor has skyrocketed, driving population growth, while many residential units have been converted into overnight rentals. Together, these factors have created a severe shortage of affordable housing for long term residents and newcomers alike. In light of this, it is understandable why so many Grand County residents oppose the development of any new overnight accommodations, which have the potential to exacerbate this problem.
  
  One of our core beliefs is that travel and accommodation providers have an obligation to the communities in which they operate. This commitment means working to minimize and mitigate the negative impacts of our activities and ensuring that they have a positive impact on resident’s quality of life. We also recognize that our long-term success depends upon attracting and retaining dedicated and talented employees, which is next to impossible if they can’t find a place to live.
  
  This is why we have allocated $2 million in our budget to develop off site affordable housing for our employees. We have also included five onsite employee housing units, which is the maximum number allowed per the county’s land use code. For the purposes of our OAO application, our project has been classified as a campground, thus exempting us from the requirement to comply with the county’s assured housing standards. And it is our understanding that there is currently no mechanism in place that would allow us to opt-in to the program voluntarily or to solidify our commitment to developing new housing stock for our employees. Based on our calculations, $2 million would allow us to develop additional housing for approximately 16 employees.
  
  We would welcome the opportunity to work with the county to find a way to include this commitment in our application or to create a mechanism that would allow us to voluntarily opt in to the existing assured housing standard.
  
  Sincerely,
  
  Matt Kareus
  
