  # Moab, Utah Officials Approve a Glamping Eco-Resort
  
  by [Woodalls Campground Magazine](https://woodallscm.com/author/woodalls-campground-magazine/)
  
  [January 24, 2024](https://woodallscm.com/moab-utah-officials-approve-a-glamping-eco-resort/)
  
  in [Industry News](https://woodallscm.com/category/industry-news/)
  
  [0](https://woodallscm.com/moab-utah-officials-approve-a-glamping-eco-resort/#comments)
  
  ![Developer Matt Kareus said he took the time to understand the challenges facing Moab and adjusted his proposal in response.Photo by Gwen Dilworth](https://www.moabtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/04-entrada-approved-1-meeting-1024x683.jpg)Developer Matt Kareus said he took the time to understand the challenges facing Moab and adjusted his proposal in response. Photo by Gwen Dilworth
  
  At long last, the luxury glamping “eco-resort” Entrada Moab has gotten the green light to pitch its tents at the intersection of highways 191 and 313, according to _**[The Times-Independent](https://www.moabtimes.com/articles/county-approves-glamping-eco-resort/)**_.
  
  The Grand County (Utah) Commission approved an overnight accommodations zoning overlay for the development — the first it has approved in over a year and a half — at their Jan. 16 meeting in a 6-1 vote, with Commissioner Trish Hedin dissenting.
  
  The developer, Matt Kareus of Fort Collins, Colorado said he hopes the site will be open in a year and a half to two years. The development will still be required to submit a site plan and receive plat approval.
  
  Commissioners cited the project’s conservation easement, employee housing and its small impact compared to development allowable under the site’s current zoning as reasons for their support.
  
  The 16-unit retreat will include an activity center, two swimming pools and trails. It anticipates an average daily rate of $2,000 per unit and projects that the Transient Room Tax revenue generated from the project will be comparable to a 150-room hotel charging $200 a night.
  
